ce:section.ce:para:
Another interesting feature of the present bimetallic alloy nanoparticles is its multi-functionality as a dual read-out sensor. Other than the colorimetric pathway, there is a fluorescent route which reports the selective etching of silver from bimetallic alloy through the restoration of the PL signal of C-dots. In this context, an energy transfer pair is constructed based on bimetallic AuAg alloy as PL acceptor and C-dots as the fluorescent donors. In an efficient energy transfer process (NSET), the emission spectrum of donor overlaps with the absorption spectrum of acceptor. Apart from NSET, inner filter effect (IFE) [48–50] is another possibility in the present system for suppression of C-dots PL signal. IFE is a process in fluorescence spectroscopy which is attributed to the attenuation of excitation and/or emission light intensities of a fluorophore by light absorbers [49]. When the total UV–Vis intensity of the light absorber at the fluorescence excitation and/or emission wavelengths of fluorophore is less than 0.05, no IFE is observed [51]. In the present system, the SPR absorption band of Au0.4Ag0.6@C-dots coincides well with the emission spectrum of bare C-dots (Fig. 6
                        A). Additionally, the absorption value of the alloy at the emission wavelength of C-dots is about 0.7 which is high enough for IFE to take place. However, regardless of the mechanism involved in PL suppression or enhancement, the outcome is the same. The PL of bare C-dots is dramatically decreased (85.5%) when C-dots are hybridized with bimetallic Au-Ag nanoparticles (Fig. 6B, (a)). Addition of excess chlorine to Au0.4Ag0.6@C-dots restored the PL signal to 216% of its quenched value (Fig. 6B, (b)). Selective etching of Ag resulted in the SPR red shift of the acceptor, so the spectral overlap of the donor-acceptor decreased. Also, by partial removal of Ag, the extinction coefficient of hybrid nanoparticle decrease so less light is absorbed. Interruption of either IFE or NSET gives rise to PL enhancement (Fig. 6C). However, as Fig. 6B shows, the fluorescence signal is not recovered to its initial value (The initial fluorescence signal of bare C-dots). This is due to the presence of Au in the nanoparticle structure. This reflects that the remaining Au prevents the fluorescence signal to be recovered completely. Addition of excess chlorine removes the maximum amount of Ag from the bimetallic structure. After that, the fluorescence signal does not increase anymore which is the result of sheer presence of gold over C-dots. The observed PL enhancement at 440 nm was linearly correlated with chlorine over the concentration range of 1.4–14 μM (inset of Fig. 6C). The DL was measured as 5.1 × 10−7 M comparable to the DL of the colorimetric pathway (DL = 6.2 × 10−7 M). The DL and linear range of the present system is comparable or in some cases better than other nanoparticles-based methods for assaying chlorine (Table 1
                        ). The digital photos of Au0.4Ag0.6@C-dots, and Au0.4Ag0.6@C-dots after treatment with excess chlorine under the ultraviolet lamp with excitation wavelength of 365 nm is presented in Scheme 1.

A sample of tap water was taken from Shiraz, Iran. Bleach liquid was purchased from Bojeneh Company, Iran. Tap water sample was free of chlorine while chlorine was presented in the bleach as claimed on the bleach bottle. The amount of chlorine in bleach was determined spectrophotometrically by measuring the absorbance value at 290 nm (ε
                        290 = 350 M−1 cm−1). Certain concentrations of freshly prepared chlorine standard solution were added to both samples. The same experimental conditions used for developing the calibration curve were applied for real sample analysis. After 10 min incubation at room temperature, the absorbance of solutions at 450 nm was recorded. Analysis of spiked real samples revealed recovery percentage values over the range of 98.07–106.25% (Table 2
                        ) suggesting the potential applicability of the present assay in environmental monitoring. Similarly, the recovery results gained through the fluorimetric channel of the system showed satisfactory results (Table 2). Particularly, the ClO− concentration in the bleach sample was successfully measured through both colorimetric and fluorimetric pathways of the probe. The concentration determined using the present system was in close agreement with the value measured spectrophotometrically.
